                        <provenance type="found" when="1839">Discovered in <date>1839?</date>. It was part of a complex series of monuments, including another ogham stone (I-COR-006), of which this is the sole survivor above ground. Macalister (1945, 62-3) supplies an inventory from one of <ref target="https://www.ria.ie/windele-collection">Windele's notebooks</ref> of what was to be seen here in his time.  'Dallaun' is marked on the 1842 OS 6-inch map outside the NW corner of a now levelled square enclosure (CO052-039002-). This would correspond reasonably with the present position of this ogham stone (<ref target="https://www.archaeology.ie/archaeological-survey-ireland/historic-environment-viewer-application">Archaeological Survey of Ireland, SMR ID: CO052-039001-</ref>). However, Macalister (1945, 63), quoting Windele, described four standing stones inside the enclosure, of which he says this was one.  
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance type="observed" when="2017">In situ in pasture, on a N-facing slope. Visited and 3d recorded for the Ogham in 3D project in August <date>2017</date>.
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
